DHCP Server Configuration in Windows Server
Definition

DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol) automatically assigns:

IP Address

Subnet Mask

Default Gateway

DNS Server
to client computers in a network.

Requirement

Windows Server installed

Static IP configured on Server

Active Directory Domain Services installed

Logged in as Domain Administrator

Example Used
Network: 192.168.1.0
Subnet Mask: 255.255.255.0
DHCP Range: 192.168.1.100 â€“ 192.168.1.200
Gateway: 192.168.1.1
DNS Server: 192.168.1.10

PART 1: Install DHCP Role
Step 1: Open Server Manager

Login to Windows Server

Open Server Manager

Step 2: Add Roles and Features

Click Manage

Select Add Roles and Features

Click Next

Select Role-based or feature-based installation

Click Next

Select Local Server

Click Next

Step 3: Select DHCP Server Role

Select DHCP Server

Click Add Features

Click Next

Click Install

PART 2: Authorize DHCP Server
Step 1: Complete DHCP Configuration

After installation, click Complete DHCP Configuration

Select Use current credentials

Click Commit

Click Close

PART 3: Create DHCP Scope
Step 1: Open DHCP Console

Open Server Manager

Click Tools

Select DHCP

Step 2: Create New Scope

Expand IPv4

Right-click IPv4

Click New Scope

Click Next

Step 3: Scope Name

Enter Scope Name:

Office_Network


Click Next

Step 4: IP Address Range

Start IP:

192.168.1.100


End IP:

192.168.1.200


Subnet Mask:

255.255.255.0


Click Next

Step 5: Exclusions (Optional)

Add excluded IPs if needed

Click Next

Step 6: Lease Duration

Default: 8 Days

Click Next

Step 7: Configure DHCP Options

Select Yes, I want to configure these options now

Click Next

Step 8: Default Gateway

Enter:

192.168.1.1


Click Add

Click Next

Step 9: DNS Server

Domain Name:

company.local


DNS Server IP:

192.168.1.10


Click Add

Click Next

Step 10: Activate Scope

Select Yes, activate this scope

Click Next

Click Finish

PART 4: Verify DHCP Working
On Client Machine

Open Command Prompt

Run:

ipconfig /release
ipconfig /renew
ipconfig /all

Verification

Client receives IP automatically

Gateway and DNS are assigned

Client can access domain and internet

PART 5: Common DHCP Commands
ipconfig /all
ipconfig /renew
ipconfig /release

Conclusion

DHCP Server has been successfully installed, authorized, and configured in Windows Server.
Client machines are now receiving IP addresses automatically.
